            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                 
                Also during my senior year I set a goal of having a date at least once a week and not dating any girl twice during the year. I almost achieved the goal. I did have at least one date a week but I did date one girl twice. I had asked her to a dance earlier in the year then in the spring, she asked me to take her to the Job’s Daughter’s Ball, a dance where the girls asked the boys for the date. Since she and I had been friends for quite awhile, I agreed. <br /><br />

                The day after graduation from high school, I was off to a U.S. Forest Service camp in the woods on the northwest side of Priest Lake. It was a camp of college students and recent high school grads who were hired to engage in the control of the White Pine Blister Rust. The pay was $1.35 an hour and we paid about $2.00 a day for room and board. The “room” consisted of a four-man canvas wall tent with an army cot, a mattress, a sleeping bag and a sheet metal wood burning stove for heat if needed. “Board” was three meals a day. There was a huge breakfast, lunch was whatever you wanted to make and carry along with you. Dinner in the evening was so big it would make your eyes bug out. After dinner, desserts and snacks were available until lights out at 10:00pm. 
 
            </span>
            
            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory0-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory0');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory0" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                The work was not really hard or demanding, in fact it was quite boring. But it was the best paying job I had ever had up to that point. We were guaranteed 40 hours pay a week, and for all hours over 40 we were paid time and a half. So, if it rained one day we just sat around camp in the tents and didn’t get paid. Then we worked on Saturday for straight time. Thus, when it rained, we hoped and prayed for it to keep up for more than one day. That way we could sit around camp and get paid after the first rainy day. That never happened though. When it did rain it only did so one day out of a week. <br /><br />

                One of the guys found a white-tailed deer fawn still with it’s spots that he thought had been abandoned. He stuffed it inside his shirt and brought it back to camp. That evening, a car load of guys got in a car and drove the 20 miles or so to the town of Priest River to a drug store where they bought a couple of baby bottles which we used to feed the fawn until it could graze. We named him, yes...Bambi. He had the run of the camp and loved being with all the guys there. Almost every night, after lights out, he would come into my tent and jump up on my cot, nestle around a bit and then settle down to sleep with me. <br /><br />

                After a couple of months, we came back to camp one evening to learn that the camp boss, who didn’t approve of us having Bambi, had radioed to headquarters to have them send for a game warden to come get the deer. Bambi was gone. None of the guys were very happy about it, but the camp boss was the boss and his word was law. A couple of months later, after the season was over and I was attending the Bonner County fair, I went into the Idaho Fish and Wildlife exhibit and there, in a chain link stockade was a deer that I thought looked a lot like Bambi. I gave it the whistle we used for Bambi in the camp, and his ears flicked up and he looked around. I whistled again and he came right over to me. We both had a good time there I think. He nuzzled and licked me and I scratched and patted him through the chain link. It was kind of sad when I turned and walked away. <br /><br />

                After working the summer in the Forest Service, I worked off and on with my brother-in-law Jack for a man who had an automobile body &amp; fender repair shop. My job was to mask off the chrome and glass of cars which were to be painted. Then after the painting was finished and dry, I removed the tape and paper. Really a “duh” type of job. <br /><br />

                One day just before I went into the army, we had a cat that was sick and had diarrhea. We had taken it to a vet to no avail and the decision was to have it put down. I told Mother it was stupid to take it back to the vet and pay him more money to do it. I would just take the thing to the city dump and shoot it with my pistol. I put the cat in a cardboard box in the front seat of the car and started off. A block from home the cat started climbing out of the box and while trying to get it back in so it wouldn’t poop all over my car seat, I ran off the road and rammed into a large tree, totaling my car. The impact sent me flying into the steering wheel with my mouth bending it over and my head hit the windshield so hard it was knocked out onto the hood of the car. The bridge part of my glasses which goes over the nose had embedded itself under the skin on my nose. <br /><br />

                So, I picked up the cat and walked back home bleeding from a cut at the hairline on my forehead, from the cut where the glasses had embedded themselves in my nose, bleeding from inside my nose and from my mouth. All were very superficial cuts, and by the time I walked the block back home, most had stopped bleeding but my face and shirtfront was pretty much covered with blood. As I walked in the back door into the kitchen, Mother, in an adjoining room asked why I was back already. I said I had had a wreck. She asked, “You what?” And stepped to the doorway to see me standing there in my bloody splendor. She let out a cry and started to crumple. I had to attend to her and assure her I was OK, and get her to sit down before I could go the bathroom, clean myself up and tend to the cuts. Poor mother. <br /><br />

                I remember the day my mother went with me to the bus depot when I left for basic training in the army. I was excited, ready to start an adventure. She was losing a son. I can still remember the look of pain and the tears on her face as the bus pulled away from the curb. 

                </span>
