            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            bill roos
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">At that time, all men over the age of 18 had the obligation to serve in the military unless physical or mental condition warranted them for being exempt. So, I decided to enlist in the Army and get that part of my life over with. 

            <br />
            </span>
            <!--div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/124071354" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “She said, ‘Yes,’ and my jaw really hit the floor.”
                </span>
            </div-->

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                Thus, on the 30th of November, 1954, I boarded the bus to Spokane, where I went to the military induction center and was sworn in as a member of the United States Army, along with about 20 other guys. We were then loaded onto a train and off we went to Fort Ord, California, arriving there about 6:00am the next day. At Fort Ord, I spent 8 weeks in basic training. It was supposed to be tough but for me it wasn’t. I was in the best physical shape I had ever been in from spending the summer in the Forest Service. My legs were very strong and the long marches we had in basic training that were hard on others, were easy for me. On one march of about 15 miles, we carried all of our gear, field packs, rifle, canteen, bayonet and steel helmet, only about 25 pounds total. That was light compared to the packs I had carried into the mountains camping, which weighed around 40 pounds or so. I was among the 30 or so who finished the march out of the company of 200. Most of us who finished had done so carrying not only all of our own gear but part of some other man’s as well, so they wouldn’t drop out of the march. When we got back, I learned that the man whose rifle I had carried for about the last 5 miles had dropped out anyway. So, I stuck his rifle into the ground barrel first and left it there for him to find. <br /><br /> 

                One of the hardest days I had was the day we lined up in the mess hall and walked between two medics who each gave us a vaccination, a tetanus shot in the left arm and a typhoid shot in the right. Both of those shots carried a whallop! Immediately the arms began to hurt as though some big monster had slugged me in each arm. 

            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                    After all had received their shots we were marched off to the physical training course where we did such torturous exercises as push-ups and standing with arms spread-eagle holding our 8 pound M-1 rifle by the barrel in our right hand. That is hard enough to do when your arm doesn’t hurt. By the end of the day a lot of the guys—close to a third of the company—were on sick call the next day. Some were out for two to three days. But, not me. I guess I was only meant to be miserable but not enough to be on sick call. <br /><br />

                    I had a real great time on the machine gun range. I was assigned with three other guys to an worn out .30 caliber gun which was mounted on a low tripod. You fired it by laying on your belly. One man firing and a second making sure the ammunition was feeding into the gun properly. After firing 40 or so rounds we changed places so all four of us were able to fire the weapon and be the loader. The routine was, as you pulled the trigger, you were supposed to say to yourself, “Fire a burst of six” and release the trigger. Ostensibly the gun fires six bullets in that time. Also, supposedly, it was impossible to fire less than three or four rounds at a time with a .30 caliber machine gun. Our gun was so old and worn out we soon learned we could not only fire less than three rounds but could actually fire single shots! So there I was laying on by belly popping off one shot at a time when one of the range officers came down the firing line shouting, “Who’s firing single shots?” One of the guys in our group called out, “We are.” As the officer ran over to us I was still popping off single shots and we were all laughing about it. And he asked how we were able to shoot single rounds. We told him the gun’s mechanism was so worn out and slow it was just possible. He said. “Well, it’s not supposed to be possible, so stop doing it.” After he left, the guys who had not had their turn were still firing two or three single rounds among their “bursts of six” when their turn came. <br /><br />

                    I was at Fort Ord over Christmas of 1954 and when we were issued three-day passes I took a bus to Napa, California where my mother’s brother Verl lived and spent Christmas with him, Aunt Ruth and my two cousins Don and Annette. <br /><br />

                    As basic training was nearing completion, I decided to fly home on leave, but told my parents I was taking a bus that would take longer but would be cheaper. I flew from Salinas, California to Portland, Oregon then on to Spokane where I had to spend about five or six hours waiting in the bus depot for the bus to Sandpoint. When I arrived in Sandpoint it was on a bright, clean, crisp and sunny day the first part of February. I shouldered my duffle bag that held all my uniforms and personal gear and walked the 6 blocks home. I can still hear the soles of my combat boots making chirping sounds as I walked on the hard-packed, dry snow of the street. When I got to the house, I rang the doorbell and stood waiting. Mother opened the door, saw me threw her hands up and cried out “Oh My!” then “Ah-ha-ha-ha-ha!” It was quite a surprise. <br /><br />

                    After two weeks at home, I boarded a train for Fort Benjamin Harrison, located just outside of Indianapolis, Indiana. The train took me to Chicago, where I changed trains to Indianapolis, but my luggage didn’t make the change. So, I arrived at Ft. Harrison with only the clothes on my back. It took three days before I was able to get my stuff. At Ft. Harrison I spent a little over a month in “casual status” awaiting the beginning of the next Finance Procedures class. Casual status meant we were laborers. One day half of us were on Kitchen Patrol (KP) from 5:00am till 6:00pm working in the mess hall, washing dishes, peeling potatoes, scrubbing pots and pans, sweeping and mopping floors, cleaning ovens, doing anything the cooks told us to do. The other half got to sleep in until 6:00 am and after breakfast we were assigned to work details starting at 8:00 am and working until 5:00 pm with an hour off for lunch. Thus, we had KP one day, work detail the next, then KP, then detail, day after day. The work details were a snap. But we all hated KP.<br /><br /> 

                    The first detail I was assigned to was with another guy screwing handles on new chests of drawers for officer quarters. Not difficult or hard work but boring as all get out. Other work details were doing such things as sweeping, mopping, waxing and buffing floors. But, one day I was assigned to the office at the motor pool. This was a building with an officer we hardly ever saw, and when he was there, he was sequestered in his office. There was the First Sergeant, a Corporal and a Private First Class clerk. I was first assigned to sweep, mop, wax and buff the floors. Well that only took a couple of hours, so the sergeant assigned me to go with the two clerks to wash the staff car. Now the wash area was outdoors and this was the end of February and there was snow on the ground and it was cold. As soon as we sprayed water on the car, it froze into a sheet of ice. So, back to the office we went. Now there was nothing more for me to do the whole rest of the day, so I sat around talking with the two clerks in between their spurts of doing their jobs. Finally the sergeant took me into a back room, produced a circular rack holding about twelve .45 caliber automatic pistols. He showed me how to disassemble them for cleaning, then gave me cleaning supplies. I sat there the rest of the day cleaning those pistols. As I recall, I finished about two-thirds of them. The next day, I did my KP bit and the next day—surprise, I was assigned back to the motor pool office where I was warmly welcomed, and put to work sweeping and buffing the floor. Then back to the pistol rack to finish the job I had started two days before. When I finished, I went out and told the sergeant I was finished and asked what he had for me to do next. He looked me in the eye and said I was far too fast in getting my work done. I was to go back and clean all of the pistols again but to make the job last. I did so. The next day, off to KP. The next day, I was informed that the motor pool had requested I be assigned there every day so that was where I was to go. I was excused from KP. It was too good to be true, however, as after about a week of going to the motor pool and not having KP, someone higher up determined I was to take my turn doing KP. <br /><br />

                    Finally classes started with 40 men. Thirteen weeks later, 39 graduated, one having failed about midway through the course and re-assigned to Fort Knox, Kentucky to become a crew member of a tank. The courses we took were military pay, commercial accounting, payment of commercial accounts and typing. For typing, we were all given a typing test and based on the results were divided into two classes, beginning and advanced. I scored 31 words per minute with one error with my hunt-and-peck method and was placed in the beginners class to be taught touch typing. The course was 50 hours long, about 5 hours a week. At the end, I was able to touch type 32 words a minute with two errors. Net improvement: zero. After my permanent assignment, I ended up handling the pay records of a battalion and straight typing was never a part of my job. What the job entailed was typing a 50% to 60% ratio of numbers mixed with letters. A chore which I found too cumbersome to do by touch typing, so I returned to hunt-and-peck and got along fine. <br /><br />

                    I had applied to be assigned to fill one of the vacancies at Camp Chaffee, Arkansas after graduation. I wanted to spend some time stateside so I could go home on leave again before going overseas and I thought Arkansas would be an interesting place to be. As it turned out, I spent the remainder of my enlistment there. <br /><br />

                    Four of us from our class arrived at Ft. Chaffee in June 1955 and it was HOT! We all thought we had been assigned to hell. The Finance Office where we worked had fans all over the place—no air conditioning. In fact, no building was air conditioned, not even the Division headquarters. The year after I arrived, they air-conditioned several buildings including the post library and enlisted men’s service club which were two blocks up the street from my barracks. Every evening after work, I would rush back to the barracks, change into civilian clothes, hit the mess hall for dinner then make a beeline for the library until it closed. Then I dashed across a parking lot to the service club where I would stay until they closed at 9:30 pm. Then, I had to go back to the oven of the barracks where we all would lay on our bunks not moving because to do so would cause us to sweat even more than we already were. <br /><br />

                    Eventually, the night air cooled off somewhat and we could sleep. Before there were air-conditioned places to go, all we could do was suffer the heat and humidity of Arkansas in the summer. Winters though, were heaven to us northern boys. My first Christmas there, a buddy from Northern Minnesota and one from northern New York laid around sun bathing until Christmas dinner was served. Then after dinner, took off to try to find a lake where we could rent a boat and water skis.. We found places where they would rent a boat but no skis. They thought we were nuts to even think of water skiing in December. <br /><br />

                    In November 1955, I went home on two weeks leave and while there I received the Melchezidek Priesthood and was ordained an Elder by my father on November 13th. On March 11, 1956, at the direction of the Central States Mission President, Alvin R. Dyer (who years later, served as a counselor in the First Presidency), I was set apart as a Military Group Leader for the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints by Arthur R. Anderson, Branch President of the Fort Smith, Arkansas Branch of the Church. I was then responsible for conducting Sacrament Meetings each Sunday at one of the chapels at Fort Chaffee for those soldiers who were unable to go to town to attend church. <br /><br />

                    As stated earlier, I was in charge of the pay records of a battalion and every month dealt with the company commanders and their executive officers who came to the office to pick up the payroll money for their men. After months of dealing with them, we all were on first-name (well, it was really a last-name basis as I was referred to as Roos and I called them by their last name) basis with each other and rank really didn’t enter into our dealings. Toward the end of my tour, when I would be out and about the post and saw one of the officers I knew, we would wave at each other rather than salute. Pretty lax military discipline. 
                </span>
            </div>

