        <div id="boxmodex2" class="clearfix">
            <span id="Chapter_Title_Mod">
            “You’re in the Army Now”
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            bill roos
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">
            On the 30th of November 1954 I was sworn in and began a three-year enlistment in the U.S. Army. There are a few interesting events I experienced during those three years.
            <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                       <iframe width="100%" height="166" scrolling="no" frameborder="no" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/199140260%3Fsecret_token%3Ds-J7vOr&amp;color=c8c8c8&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false"></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “I had command over close to a thousand captains, lieutenants, sergeants, and trainees.”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                
                The first happened while I was in basic training at Fort Ord, California. It was on a balmy January day that our training battalion and one other went to the rifle range to fire the M1 rifle for qualification. <br /><br />

                The army had four levels of qualification based on the score a soldier achieved firing from four different body positions. The first was the prone position at 500 yards from the target, sitting at 300 yards, kneeling at 200 yards and standing at 100 yards. The highest award was Expert Rifleman, then came the award of Marksman followed by Sharpshooter and those who failed to qualify for any of those three awards, were referred to bolos indicating that all they were good for was carrying a bolo knife which was a type of a machete. 

                
            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstoryb-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstoryb');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstoryb" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                    The firing range was stretched out in a long line with about 100 firing positions. There was a 30-foot tall control tower located mid-way along the line where the range officer sat and controlled all that went on along the line. He was in complete charge and his orders were to be obeyed without fail, even by other officers on the ground along the line.<br /><br />

                    Everyone was at the last line, which was 100 yards from the targets, firing from the standing position. I enjoyed firing weapons. I earned the highest rating possible, the Expert Rifleman badge with the M-1 rifle, a feat I attribute to all the shooting I had done growing up. I was among the first group to finish firing one day, and was standing around watching others shoot. It had been a long, long day, we had eaten lunch, the sun was warm and I had finished qualifying and was looking in vain for somewhere I could sit and take a nap. I was walking below the control tower when the range officer called to me. He asked if I had finished firing and when I answered yes, he told me to climb up the ladder and come into the tower.<br /><br />

                    The inside of the tower wasn’t very large, maybe six feet square. The bottom 30 inches was enclosed all around, but above that level, it was open on all four sides with a good view of the firing line and out to the targets. There was a microphone resting on a shelf fastened to the wall below the opening facing the target area and two folding chairs.<br /><br />

                    A young First Lieutenant occupied one chair and after we returned salutes, he ordered me to sit in the other chair. He explained it had been a long day, he had been out late the night before and he wanted to catch a short nap. In short, I was to be the acting range officer. He explained how the microphone switch worked, told me that since I had been on the range all day, I should know how the program went, told me to wake him up when the firing was completed, tilted his chair back, slid his Blue painted officer’s helmet over his eyes and left me to run his business. <br /><br />

                    It was a great experience, especially after a few minutes of giving orders, when I realized that I had command over close to a thousand captains, lieutenants, sergeants, and trainees. I spent a busy hour or so keeping everything running smoothly and safely along the line and enjoyed myself immensely. But still, I envied that officer having his nap, although how he could sleep with all the noise of 100 rifles being fired and my loudspeaker orders of “cease fire” and “commence firing” being given, I do not know. He must have had a very hard night the night before.<br /><br />

                    When all the firing had finished, I awoke the lieutenant, was excused, exchanged salutes, thanked him and climbed down to the ground, where I ran across a couple of buddies from my platoon who asked where I had been, as they had been sent to find me. When I told them, they wouldn’t believe me. Even the platoon sergeant didn’t believe me. Eventually though, the range officer happened to walk past our platoon as we were forming up to leave the range and as he passed, told me thanks for helping him. That put a stop to the doubting Thomases that wouldn’t believe me. Then they all wanted to know how I had been so lucky to be selected. <br /><br />

                    I told them that luck had no part in my selection. It was just obvious the lieutenant recognized a good soldier when he saw one. 
                </span>
            </div>
           

