            “Who Wants To Know?”
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            bill roos
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">
            Three months before my enlistment in the army was up, there transpired a famous event in U.S. History. The U.S. Supreme Court had ruled racial segregation in schools was illegal. In 1957, there was going to be a test case in Arkansas. Little Rock Central High School was going to be integrated with nine black students.
            <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <iframe width="100%" height="166" scrolling="no" frameborder="no" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/199140092%3Fsecret_token%3Ds-QDgfR&amp;color=cccccc&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false"></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “I...found myself looking at a Two-Star General standing some six feet from me.”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">    

                The Governor Orville Faubus used the Arkansas National Guard to block entrance by the black students under guise that the guard was there to keep the peace.<br /><br />
                     
                The black students did not attend the first day of school. On the second day, they did enter but they were met with such harsh treatment and near riot, classes were cancelled. The President of the U.S., Dwight D. Eisenhower, then sent the 101st airborne division to Little Rock to restore order. To remove the National Guard from control of the governor, he “nationalized” them. That is, they were called into the regular army under the control of the President. 
 
            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory2-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory2');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                    
                     
                    That is how I became involved.<br /><br />
                     
                    I was a Specialist 3rd class (Spec 3) assistant section chief in the divisional finance office. I was picked, along with a Sergeant First Class (SFC), to prepare a building to house a special finance office to handle the payroll of the Arkansas National Guard. We set about the task and were joined a couple of days later by a First Lieutenant, and 40 privates who were on a 120-day reserve training program from Fort Hood Texas. The Lieutenant became the commanding officer, the Sergeant became the First Sergeant and second in command. I was third in line and to begin with, was responsible for getting all the pay records printed up.<br /><br />
                     
                    The Lieutenant and the 40 privates all had quarters close by, but the Sergeant and I were both married and lived in town, about a 30-minute drive away.<br /><br />
                     
                    We worked long, long hours those first few weeks. Often, we worked until we became groggy, then would just lie down on a table and sleep for a couple of hours. I went two or three days at a time without going home, without clean clothes. One guy had an electric razor and several of us used it to shave each day. The first week, we had sandwiches, milk and coffee delivered to us so we could keep working while we ate.<br /><br />

                    About the fourth or fifth night, I and a couple of men assigned to me, were working in a room just inside the entrance to the building. It was about 9:00 pm or so and I had a radio blaring good old music of the 50’s and was singing along over the clatter of the equipment used to make the printing plates used to print the pay records and the machine that printed those records.<br /><br />
                     
                    I heard someone standing in the doorway behind me ask, “What is going on in this room?” <br /><br />

                    Without stopping work or looking around to see who was asking, I rudely responded, “Who wants to know?”<br /><br />
                     
                    Then before any answer came, I looked around and found myself looking at a Two-Star General standing some six feet from me. I leapt to my foot, called “Ten hut!” to the men in the room and blurted out, “I’m sorry sir, I didn't know it was—” <br /><br />

                    He cut me off and told my helpers to go on back to their work. He apologized for interrupting us and asked where he could find the officer in charge. I offered to escort him but he just asked to be given directions; he didn’t want to stop me in my work. I told him where to find the Lieutenant and he left. About half an hour later, he stopped by the room on his way out of the building and thanked us warmly for the long hours we were putting in to get the job accomplished.<br /><br />
                     
                    I rushed upstairs to where the Lieutenant and Sergeant were and found out he was the Commanding General of the Arkansas National Guard. He had learned we were working around the clock setting things up to get his men paid and decided to pay us a visit.<br /><br />
                     
                    After that, when someone behind me asked a question I always looked to see who it was before I answered.
                </span>
